By adding some logging, I have narrowed the scope down to [this block of code](https://github.com/ReactiveX/RxJava/blob/aa400d10e18ebcae1ed5abbfe342bba7e5e38a39/src/main/java/io/reactivex/NbpObservable.java#L2614-L2650).

``` java
        Observable<T> o = Observable.create(s -> {
            subscribe(new NbpSubscriber<T>() {

                @Override
                public void onComplete() {
                    s.onComplete();
                }

                @Override
                public void onError(Throwable e) {
                    s.onError(e);
                }

                @Override
                public void onNext(T value) {
                    s.onNext(value);
                }

                @Override
                public void onSubscribe(Disposable d) {
                    s.onSubscribe(new Subscription() {

                        @Override
                        public void cancel() {
                            d.dispose();
                        }

                        @Override
                        public void request(long n) {
                            // no backpressure so nothing we can do about this
                        }

                    });
                }

            });
        });
```

The NPE occurs when processing the following block of code as a "TypeDeclaration":

``` java
{
  public @Override void onComplete() {
    s.onComplete();
  }
  public @Override void onError(Throwable e) {
    s.onError(e);
  }
  public @Override void onNext(T value) {
    s.onNext(value);
  }
  public @Override void onSubscribe(Disposable d) {
    s.onSubscribe(new Subscription() {
  public @Override void cancel() {
    d.dispose();
  }
  public @Override void request(long n) {
  }
});
  }
}
```

Well, this bug is a little bit more complicate than explains in this issue.

First @JakeWharton, I think you didn't specify all dependencies of RxJava in your classpath. You need to have a correct classpath to satisfy the JDT compiler which parses the target source code. The result of JDT is used by Spoon to build its AST. You can use the noclasspath mode but it isn't stable yet.

Now, there is a real bug behind this issue when we try to build the node of a `CtInvocation`:

``` java
@SchedulerSupport(SchedulerKind.NONE)
@SuppressWarnings({ "unchecked", "rawtypes"})
public final NbpObservable<List<T>> toSortedList() {
    return toSortedList((Comparator)Comparator.naturalOrder());
}
```

The method declaration of `Comparator.naturalOrder()` is:

``` java
@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
public static <T extends Comparable<? super T>> Comparator<T> naturalOrder() {
    return (Comparator<T>) Comparators.NaturalOrderComparator.INSTANCE;
}
```

And the generic type `T` is tricky. When we want to build the return type `Comparator<T>` in a `CtTypeReference`, Spoon throws a `StackOverflowException`. JDT gives us the same instance of `T` at the beginning of the generic type and at the end (in `? super T`).

I'm working on a solution but it isn't simple.
